            I also found such a shop in the nearby shopping center. Unfortunately the tailor was not there in the morning. A friendly lady explained to me that he might get to work (if at all) around 12 noon. </p>
        <p> I spent the waiting time in a pizzeria with a glass of iced tea, which was filled up every few minutes. Since I am not really convinced of Cebu either, I decided to see how to come to Dumaguete. I found three options. Either by plane, a night ferry or bus. After looking for some time, I gave it to want to find a bus timetable on the Internet. Just drive to the bus station and look there yourself. </p>
        <p> So after 12 p.m. I made my way back to the cobbler and lo and behold, he came to work today. It took less than 10 minutes, then my bag was repaired for just under 3 euros. THANKS. </p>
        <p> When I arrived at the bus station, I walked the corridors along the buses and looked at Dumaguete as the destination. You have to say that Dumaguete is on another island called Negros, which can only be reached by ship. So many buses only bring passengers to the ferry and from there you have to continue to see yourself. </p>
